Packages and data

library(here)

If you don’t already have these packages, install them using pak::pak("package_name").

We’ll be using the 2021 World Happiness Report dataset, which contains information regarding the state of happiness in the world. It contains happiness scores and rankings from the Gallup World Poll, as well as additional information that can explain variations between countries in happiness:

  • economic production

  • social support

  • life expectancy

  • freedom

  • absence of corruption

  • generosity

happiness <- 
  read_csv("world-happiness-report-2021.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>% 
  select(
    ladder_score, # our outcome
    logged_gdp_per_capita, 
    social_support,
    healthy_life_expectancy,
    freedom_to_make_life_choices,
    generosity,
    perceptions_of_corruption
  )

Step 1: splitting

An important part of validating a model is making sure we split our data into a training set and a test set at the start. The training set is used for model development and optimization, while the test set is held out until models have been selected. The test set is then used to determine the efficacy of the models chosen.

For this dataset, we will perform:

  • stratified sampling using the default 3:1 ratio of training-to-test
  • resample the training set using five repeats of 10-fold cross-validation

This can be achieved using functions from the {rsample} packages, which creates a special “split” object.

set.seed(420)

# splitting 
happiness_splits <- initial_split(happiness, strata = ladder_score) 
happiness_train <- training(happiness_splits)
happiness_test <- testing(happiness_splits)

# 10-fold cross validation
happiness_folds <-
  happiness_train %>% 
  vfold_cv(strata = ladder_score, repeats = 5)

We can inspect our split object:

happiness_splits
## <Analysis/Assess/Total>
## <109/40/149>

Step 2: our “recipes”

The {recipe} package allows you to specify the role of each variable, and any pre-processing steps you will require. To set up a “recipe”:

  1. Specify the formula using (recipe()): specify the role of each variable, into outcome or predictor variables

  2. Specify pre-processing steps using (step_*()): define the pre-processing steps (e.g. normalization, interaction terms, principal component analysis, etc.)

In our case, we will specify two recipes: - Recipe 1: for models where predictors are required to be scaled and centered - Recipe 2: for models where we want to use quadratic and interaction terms

# Recipe 1: normalized recipe
recipe_norm <-
  happiness_train %>% 
  recipe(ladder_score ~ .) %>% 
  # normalize all predictors to have SD of 1, mean of 0
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) 

# Recipe 2: polynomial recipe
recipe_poly <-
  recipe_norm %>% 
  # create new columns that are basis expansions of variables using orthogonal polynomials
  step_poly(all_predictors()) %>% 
  # create new columns that are interaction terms between all variables
  step_interact(~ all_predictors():all_predictors())

We made use of a few helper functions:

  • outcome ~ . will fit a model that predicts the outcome using all other columns.
  • all_predictors() is a role selector which allows us to apply our step_* to all predictor variables

We can inspect the summary of our “recipes”:

Step 3: specify the models

The next step is to specify our models using the {parsnip} package. The {parsnip} package is a unified interface for model selection and specification. For model selection and specification, you need:

  • The model type: the model desired, e.g. rand_forest() for a random forest, linear_reg() for linear regression, nearest_neighbor() for K-nearest neighbor, and so on. There is an incredible add-in to browse these models and copy them in to your script.

  • The engine: the underlying package the model should come from (e.g. “ranger” for the ranger implementation of Random Forest), set using set_engine().

  • The mode: the type of prediction (e.g. classification or regression), set using set_mode().

# glmnet (glm via penalized maximum likelihood)
spec_lr <- 
  linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('glmnet')

# MARS (multivariate adaptive regression splines)
spec_mars <- 
  mars(prod_degree = tune()) %>%
  set_engine('earth') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# SVM (support vector machines) - radial basis function
spec_svm_r <- 
  svm_rbf(cost = tune(), rbf_sigma = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('kernlab') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# SVM (support vector machines) - polynomial
spec_svm_p <- 
  svm_poly(cost = tune(), degree = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('kernlab') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# K-Nearest Neighbor 
spec_knn <- 
  nearest_neighbor(
    neighbors = tune(), 
    dist_power = tune(), 
    weight_func = tune()
  ) %>% 
  set_engine('kknn') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# CART (classification and regression tree)
spec_cart <- 
  decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune(), min_n = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('rpart') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Bagged decision trees
spec_cart_bag <- 
  bag_tree() %>% 
  set_engine('rpart', times = 50L) %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Random forest
spec_rf <- 
  rand_forest(mtry = tune(), min_n = tune(), trees = 200L) %>% 
  set_engine('ranger') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# XGBoost (eXtreme Gradient Boosting)
spec_xgb <- 
  boost_tree(
    tree_depth = tune(),
    learn_rate = tune(), 
    loss_reduction = tune(), 
    min_n = tune(), 
    sample_size = tune(), 
    trees = 200L
  ) %>% 
  set_engine('xgboost') %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# cubist rule-based regression
spec_cube <- 
  cubist_rules(committees = tune(), neighbors = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('Cubist')

Step 4: putting it all together

Now we’ll put the model and recipes together into workflow sets. You initiate a workflow set using workflow_set() (from the {workflowsets} package) and then adding the recipes and models to it.

In our example, we will be:

  • Creating workflowsets for our 3 recipes:

    • workflowset 1: for the models using recipe_norm

    • workflowset 2: for the models using recipe_poly

    • workflowset 3: for the models not requiring any preprocessing steps

  • Combining all workflow sets above into one single workflowsets object

sets_norm <-
  workflow_set(
    preproc = list(norm = recipe_norm),
    models = list(
      svm_r = spec_svm_r,
      svm_p = spec_svm_p,
      knn = spec_knn
    )
  )

sets_poly <-
  workflow_set(
    preproc = list(norm = recipe_poly),
    models = list(lr = spec_lr, knn = spec_knn)
  )

# several recipes don't need pre-processing
# need to have a `preproc` step to use `workflowsets::workflow_variables()` 

sets_simple <- 
  workflow_set(
    preproc = list(formula(ladder_score ~.)),
    models = 
      list(
        mars = spec_mars, 
        cart = spec_cart, 
        cart_bag = spec_cart_bag,
        rf = spec_rf, 
        gb = spec_xgb, 
        cube = spec_cube
      )
  )

sets <- bind_rows(sets_norm, sets_poly, sets_simple)

Step 5: tuning

Since we have several models with parameters that we specified needed to be turned, we need to tune them to determine which parameter values lead to the best model performances before fitting our models. If we had selected models without any parameters to tune, we could have skipped this process.

In our example, we will be performing grid search via racing approach (more efficient, see Section 13.4.4) using up to 100 different parameter candidates.

ctrl_race <-
  control_race(
    save_pred = TRUE,
    parallel_over = 'everything',
    save_workflow = TRUE
  )

res_grid <-
  sets %>%
  workflow_map(
    'tune_race_anova',
    seed = 420,
    resamples = happiness_folds,
    grid = 100,
    control = ctrl_race,
    verbose = TRUE
  )

Step 6: evaluate cross-validation performance

We will be assessing cross-validation performance by:

  • using rank_results() from {workflowsets} to rank models by root mean square error (RMSE)

  • using select_best() from {tune} inside autoplot() to rank models using their best tuning parameter combination

res_ranks <-
  res_grid %>% 
  rank_results('rmse') %>% 
  filter(.metric == 'rmse') %>% 
  select(wflow_id, model, .config, rmse = mean, rank) %>% 
  group_by(model) %>% 
  slice_min(rank, with_ties = FALSE) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(rank)

  select_best = TRUE

Step 7: evaluate performance on test set

The final steps involve choosing the best model and evaluating its performance on the test set by:

  • using pull_workflow_set_result() from {workflowsets} to extract the best workflow
  • using finalize_workflow() and last_fit() from {tune} to fit on the full training set
  • using collect_metrics() from {tune} to see results on the test set
  • using collect_predictions() from {tune} to extract the test set predictions
wflow_id_best <- 
  res_ranks %>% 
  slice_min(rank, with_ties = FALSE) %>% 
  pull(wflow_id)

wflow_id_best
## [1] "norm_svm_p"
wf_best <-
  res_grid %>% 
  pull_workflow_set_result(wflow_id_best) %>% 
  select_best(metric = 'rmse')

Step 8: stack ’em (optional!)

{stacks} is a tidymodels package for ensembling, a process that involves “combining” the output of many candidate models to generate a new model, which often has superior predictive performance.

The “combining” of the candidate models involves fitting a regularized linear model to the predictions of the candidate models. Essentially, the outputs of the candidate models serve as predictors for the true outcome variable.

Each candidate model has a stacking coefficient. The higher the stacking coefficient, the more influential that candidate member’s predictions will be in the ensemble’s predictions. If the stacking coefficient is zero, it is not retained.

Implementation-wise, the flow is the following:

  1. Define candidate ensemble members
  2. Collect candidates
  3. Initialize a data_stack object with stacks()
  4. Iteratively adding candidate ensemble members to the data_stack with add_candidates()
  5. Evaluate how to combine their predictions with blend_predictions()
  6. Fit candidate ensemble members with non-zero stacking coefficients with fit_members()
  7. Predict on new data with predict()

From Simon Couch’s {stacks} talk:

Let’s go through the remaining steps:

  • initialize the stack with stacks()
  • add the candidate models with add_candidates()
happiness_data_st <-
  stacks() %>% 
  add_candidates(res_grid)
  • “combine” the predictions of the data stack with blend_predictions()
  • fit the candidates with non-zero stacking coefficients on the full training set
happiness_model_st <-
  happiness_data_st %>%
  blend_predictions()

happiness_model_st <-
  happiness_model_st %>%
  fit_members()
  • get predictions with predict()
happiness_test <- 
  happiness_test %>%
  bind_cols(predict(happiness_model_st, .))
member_preds <- 
  happiness_test %>%
  select(ladder_score) %>%
  bind_cols(predict(happiness_model_st, happiness_test, members = TRUE))

  map_dfr(member_preds, rmse, truth = ladder_score, data = member_preds) %>%
  mutate(member = colnames(member_preds))
